Description. Active postlarval forms. Standard measurements given in
Table 1
. Body oval in outline (
Fig. 1
). Gnathosoma. Chelicera composed of base and cheliceral claw ( digitus mobilis ). Cheliceral blade (in side view) serrated across in proximal part, and along inner edge in distal part. Pedipalp typical of Trombidiidae , without modified, spine-like setae. About 3–5 smooth, whip-like setae placed on palp tibia, close to odontus base (
Fig. 2
). Remaining setae on palps setulose. Odontus simple. Palp tarsus (
Fig 2
) either equal to or slightly extending beyond termination of palp tibial claw. Several solenidia present at tip of segment.

Idiosoma, dorsum. Anterior margin of aspidosoma (
Fig. 3
) concave. Crista metopica composed of anterior process, sensillary area and posterior process. Anterior process of crista short, formed of two linear, cuticular swellings, not clearly delimited in their anterior parts. Sensillary area (
Fig. 3
) oval, located in anterior part of crista. Sensillary setae covered with tiny barbs, distributed predominantly along medial part of setae. Posterior process of crista slightly and gradually narrowing towards end, rounded at termination. Eyes pedunculate, situated at level of sensillary area of crista. Each eye composed of double lens; anterior lens larger than posterior one. Eye peduncles slightly narrowed at base and rounded apically, without distinct angle formed between one of peduncle’s sides and lens plane. Setae at anterior part of aspidosoma more slender, gradually pass into more robust setae towards opisthosoma termination.

Idiosoma, venter. Ventral setae (
Fig. 7
) more slender than those covering dorsal side of opisthosoma. Setules covering VS much longer than in DS, with basal parts lined up in distinct rims extended alongside setal stems (cross section of seta three-axial). Genital sclerites of female and male comparable in proportion (
Fig. 5
) with two pairs of genital papillae. Epivalves similar in length to centrovalves; both covered by setae. Setae on epivalves with thicker stem than those on centrovalves and with more outstanding setules. Anus surrounded by valves, each valve covered with setae, more slender than VS.
